m - a Deluxe Room on a higher floor - I found it had no odor and also felt cooler (closer to a true 72 degrees). So I relocated. The downside, the room had a connecting door to the next room and I could hear the conversations as if they were in the same room. I was able to stuff towels under the significant gap beneath the door, which helped.The next day I woke up thinking I could tolerate staying my last of three nights. But my positive feelings quickly faded as I attempted to use the fitness facility and found that my key would not open the door. I had to go back down to the front desk, only to find out that my keys were still active and the door should open. She said that she'd have security meet me at the gym. I tried my keys again several times, until another patron opened the door for me. I inquired on whether he had any trouble getting in and he said that the door was a little tricky. In hindsight, I also remember the guy in front of my the day before having trouble opening the door. I waited for security and he reiterated that the door can be tricky. If you know that a door only works SOME of the time, why wouldn't you fix it?I reached my final straw when I got back to my room later in the day after sightseeing and neither of my room keys would open my own room door. Apparently the front desk attendant who switched my rooms didn't do the due dilligence to ensure that they were programmed for my two remaining nights. I went straight to my room and called SPG to be transferred to another hotel. To top it off, the same front desk attendant informed the SPG agent that I would be charged $100 for an early departure. After the steam finished exploding from my ears I told the SPG agent I would walk back downstairs and speak with the front desk attendent myself. The agent put me on hold to allow the Palace front desk attendent to drop from the line. When she came back she said that they'd decided to waive the $100 fee - as if they were doing me a favor after 3 consecutive days of problems.If you are interested in experiencing the legacy of the Palace Hotel, might I suggest you simply stop by, walk around the lobby and perhaps even visit the bar/restaurant. But do NOT pay for a room, unless you can appreciate a warm bedroom, possibly the odor of mildew/mold and you don't mind POOR SERVICE!Oh...if I had to say something nice about the hotel...they have a really nice pool, with windows all above it. And they have individual TV monitors for the cardio equipment, but they only have 3 ellipticals and 3 treadmills, so get there early or you'll be stuck on a bike.	
