Aug 13 2009 	A "Palace" It's Not!	I stayed two nights at The Palace Hotel while attending a conference there. It's a beautiful old building in an excellent location in the Financial District. It's right across the street from a BART station, making it very convenient to get to from the airport. It's also within walking distance of Chinatown, the Ferry Building, and Union Square, and a short trolley hop from Fisherman's Wharf. The front desk check-in was very good, and they had a room ready to accommodate my early arrival. The room itself has high ceilings and wonderful moldings. There is a mini-fridge, and a nice new flat screen TV.That's about it for the pros. Now for all the cons.There was a desk in one corner that's something of an afterthought, with a cheap office chair that wouldn't go high enough to comfortably use a laptop. There is one heat/air conditioning vent high up on the wall over the door to the bathroom, and it blows directly across the bed and straight at the desk. If you're trying to use the desk, you end up sitting in a continual stream of ice-cold air. So every few minutes I would readjust the thermostat to stop the cold air, and the room would get hot and stuffy in no time. I would have liked to use the window, which was supposed to open, but it was stuck shut. Same problem at night, since the AC also blows right across the bed.There was wireless Internet in the lobby, which was being used by all of the people at the conference. I wanted to use it in the room as well, but couldn’t connect. I called the front desk, and was told that Internet in the room as $16.95 per day! All of the non-paying people in the lobby could use it for free, but the paying guests in the room had to pony up 17 bucks. Absolutely ridiculous!The bathroom is cute, but definitely on the small side. The door partially blocks both the toilet and the shower. Some of the grout was missing or dirty between the tiles, and the tub definitely shows its age.Housekeeping and maintenance were terrible for a 4-star hotel. Some of the furniture – which is on the battered side –was dusty. The front cover was coming off the desk phone, which also had a layer of dust on it. The soap dish in the shower still had remnants of old soap in it. The carpets were showing wear and dirt. The wall lamps in the bathroom were hanging crooked, and the shades on both of them had frayed edges and spots of who-knows-what. There was not even a pen and a pad of paper in the room!There was no in-room coffee. (I assume that’s because they would prefer that you order breakfast in the room, which with tax, tip, and delivery charge would have been pushing $40 each for just a basic breakfast.) There was, however, a bottle of some type of fancy water next to the TV, which you could have for a mere $7. It was covered with dust and the seal on it was partially broken, so I wouldn’t have trusted drinking it despite its hefty price tag.Then there was the noise. I could hear every banging door and every conversation out in the hallway. Worst of all was the snoring coming from the person in the next room. It was so loud I literally felt like he was in the room with me. I realize that this is an old building, but the walls were worse than a cheap motel. Other than the great location, I really don’t see anything special about this hotel, especially for the price. It’s definitely seen better days, despite its supposed recent renovation. There are any number of good hotels and motels in San Francisco, so do yourself a favor and choose something other than The Palace.	
