Jun 28 2009 	Call the Palace and check on specials	The Palace is one of the oldest hotels in San Francisco but has been updated. I thought the rooms were great--big with high ceilings. It is located in the financial district which means lots of restaurants do not keep late hours and some aren't open on the weekends and that the closest coin laundry is 7 or 8 blocks away. But both the Bart and cable cars are just steps away from the hotel entrance on Market. It is easy walking distance to Chinatown and North Beach so good food can be found close by. If you are there on a Saturday the library sponsors a hotel tour that is fascinating and you get to see rooms that are generally closed to the public. The hotel has had its share of famous people and scandal. The staff is helpful and friendly; the concierges went out of their way to accommodate us. We got a terrific deal on our rooms from Thursday through Sunday--$135 per night plus a coupon worth $25 ($25 for each room) at one of the restaurants or for room service. For the days before the room was $200. I'd suggest calling and see what can be arranged. Because of its location, this is a hotel that is most likely full during the week so is more likely to have weekend specials. The downside of this is that the fitness room is chock full of people at 7 am. during the week. It has a good assortment of equipment but I had to use it after 8:30 or so. There is an indoor pool and hot tub along with a nicely appointed women's locker room (I can't vouch for the men's). Here are my gripes about the hotel. WiFi in the rooms costs $18.95/day plus tax. I presume they do this because many travelers are on business and this can be charged to their expense accounts. There is free WiFi in the lobby and public areas of the hotel. Parking is $48/day. The Hearst parking lot is located very close to the hotel (main entrance is on New Montgomery--turn right at 1st street (Jesse) and then right again on Annie, then left an into the parking lot. If you miss this turn right on 3rd St. and enter from there.) They charge $20/day with no in and out privileges---however, all you have to do is pay and then re-park and it doesn't cost any more (unless you take it out more than once the same day). It is important that you check the hours for Hearst--it doesn't open until 10 am on Sunday.	
