Jun 4 2009 	San Francisco Palace with 10 year old boy	For Spring Break in March, we took our 10 year old son to the Palace in San Francisco for 4 days (after time in Arizona, the Grand Canyon and vegas). We had a very nice one bedroom suite, with a comfortable pull out couch in the living room and a large bedroom but a small and dated bathroom. The hotel, an old style and elegant hotel with extremely long hallways, was well located to Union Square, but we found that we spent most of our time down by the Wharf, so we probably would have been better off staying down there. I picked the Palace because it had a pool, but we never had time to use it! Breakfast was in the beautiful garden court -- a delicious but expensive buffet. There are less expensive places nearby but my son really enjoyed it so we went every day. The concierges were helpful as to children's activities as well as restaurants that were good but still family friendly (we went to Two (near the hotel, not so family friendly), Houstons, Fog City Diner). He loved the Exploratoreum -- we went twice, Alcatraz, and Pier 39 where they have a bungee trampoline thing overlooking the marina. We had a ball on the famous Fire Engine Tour, and learned all about the fire history of San Francisco (tour leaves from the Cannery and goes through the Presidio and then over the GG Bridge to Sausalito and back) -- the husband and wife team that run it are a real hoot with great stories and even songs -- she will even tap dance for you when you get back!! It is corny but very fun and made you smile! We also went to Muir Woods and Sausalito on our own, rode the cable cars, went to the Cable Car Museum, Coit Tower, Lombard Street, walked through the Little Italy and Chinatown (all the things you would expect). We also took a behind the scenes tour of ATT Park -- the guide was so knowledgeable and the park was so nice-- I think that was the highlight of the trip for my son! Luckily the weather was beautiful and sunny every day, if a little crisp. There is definitely enough to do for 3 days in San Fran with a kid, but beyond that you really need to hit the road to the environs.	
