Oct 23 2008 	Lovely and Gracious	I did a lot of research on this hotel beforehand, but there were some nice surprises. This is a very beautiful, historic hotel with some unusually breathtaking architectural features. The courtyard, formerly where horses and buggies arrived, is stunning. There is a pool one of the upper floors, which we unfortunately did not have time to visit. High ceilings and marble everywhere. The rooms are lovely and clean. The most outstanding thing about the hotel, however, is the people that work there. They really seem interested in making your stay exceptional. Extremely friendly and efficient, but not pushy. We paid less than half of the AAA rate for the room for two days, but we were treated very well. I was fully expecting an attitude at check-in, but the gentleman was very helpful, beyond the usual. Asked for and actually received a quiet room! The only bad aspects: I always find hotel beds way too uncomfortable, didn't expect anything else, so almost no sleep. Yikes! The parking is $48 per day, with unlimited use. I was a little miffed because I read another review that mentioned $40 per day parking. Oh, well. I researched parking before we went, and that's not terribly out of line. We loved it.	
Oct 17 2008 	Beautiful hotel but overrated	The Palace Hotel is a beautiful old-style hotel-- tall ceilings, beautiful lobby, pretty meeting and eating areas. The staff was very friendly.But as far as hotels, and specifically, luxury hotels go- it is way overrated.The rooms are spartan with the basics- comfortable bed, a desk and a reading chair. There was, at least, a nice flat screen TV.If you're planning to try and get any work done- go somewhere else. The desk phone is antiquated and cheap, and because cell-phone coverage within those beautiful brick walls is pretty much non-existent, you'll end up having to use it anyway. There is wired internet for a exorbitant daily rate (no wireless in the hotel, so your daily rate won't help you in the lobby or meeting rooms).I wouldn't stay here again. There are better hotels, nearby.	
Oct 4 2008	Not a Luxury Hotel	Calling this a luxury hotel is a joke. It should be out of the Starwood Luxury Collection chain. Doors slam and most floors are noisy. There is no chance of sleeping past 8 a.m. with all the noise. Any trash or room service left in the hallway can stay for days. I saw one package of used wine glass sit there for two days. The phones in my room did not work properly. Maintenance is deferred. I like staying in historic hotels and I stayed here soon after the renovations were completed about ten years ago. Then the windows worked. Now, most windows do not open, so you can not get fresh air. They will send someone to prop open a window if you ask (my wait time for that was one hour, after they said it would be 10 minutes), but then you are stuck with the window in one position. Most rooms are VERY small. Most amenities are lacking, such as slippers and bath supplies. The front desk is spotty. Some nice people, some not. One front desk lady had her name tag on upside down and I think she could have cared less. The public areas are beautiful, and the dining room is historic, but the hotel is only worth it if you can get a rate for under $300. I have had more enjoyable stays at two star hotels.	
