Sep 25 2008 	Glamorous Lobby but then you get stuck in a hideous room	Our stay was for Set 19th through 23rd. Because the Oracle Convention was beginning on the 22nd, prices for the hotel, as were all nice hotels were off the charts. We managed $359 a night which seemed to be a steal because we came in on Friday. Still, all that got us was the lowest delux room without a view.I'm a Gold SPG (Sheraton) member, so I'm usually upgraded and afforded a little better -- little -- at check in. Not here. I might as well have been chop suey. For example, we checked in at 1:00 and of course, in this huge hotel, I was told rooms were not available until &quot;3:00&quot;. Turns out they pre-assign a room early in the day and if that room isn't cleaned, they will not look for another. The clerk also said a few other condesending words to me, which in turn led me to step aside and ask the porter to find the front desk manager. I received a vague apology but nothing more. I came back after lunch -- about 2:45 -- and my preassigned room was still not available, but this time a different clerk was able to find a clean room for me on a higher floor -- &quot;with an outside window.&quot;After seeing the over-the-top balcony and staying at several luxury SPG hotels throughout the world, I had some expectations. The standard hotel rooms don't even come close. (I have heard that, as with most hotels, the suites are emaculate - but as a standard traveler, this hotel does not live up to its reputation.) The beds (two doubles) squeeked and were not the Sheraton/Westen sweet sleepers. Yes, there was a nice duvet cover over the standard insert (instead of one of the Ralph Lauren's) but it wasn't the luxury fluffy duvets found at the other luxury resorts. And neither were the other linens or towels. All standard hotel class. No high count linens. No large or special towels. No special amenities in the bathrooms -- the extra small sizes were found. No cloth bags -- only plastics. Not even an ironing board -- but the iron was left on the floor of the closet! The TV, however, was new and flat and large. Ice buckets were cheap plastic. The doors to the hallway SLAMMED so you knew when everyone came and went. The walls were paper thin so we heard all conversations with the guys next door. ALL conversations. The shower had rust on the ceiling and didn't have the standard SPG bowed shower curtain; the bathroom in its self was lack-luster: the &quot;marble&quot; was 8 inches around the sink and that was it. The rest was white porcelen with a few chips. The mirrors not treated and steamed terribly.I will commend the GREAT conceige and the GREAT porters. But the maid staff was hap-hazzard - failing to empty the ice-bucket and other random things. And none of the reception staff knew how to smile: of course, each time I went by, someone was talking or at one point, yelling, at a manager -- it appears, I wasn't the only one not happy!!! The front door staff (the guys who call the taxis) were also non-attentive and very poor and making sure there were enough taxis -- often there were long waits. I would suggest talking to the concierge for trips to the airport.Next time, I'll try the Weston or go back to the LeMeridian. This place was not worth anything!	
Sep 21 2008 	My New Favorite Hotel	After reading some of the reviews on this site, I had contemplated choosing a different hotel for my San Francisco stay. I am so happy that I chose to read other objective travel reviews/guidebooks, which encouraged me to choose this hotel. The Palace Hotel was beautiful. I have stayed at many five-star hotels around the world and my mouth dropped when I entered this hotel...absolutely beautiful. The hotel has so much historical significance for San Francisco. We took a walking tour and the tour stops at this hotel...you know you've chosen the right hotel at that point. Our room was beautiful and luxurious. The bed was extremely comfortable. The iron-work on the guest staircase was incredible. You can feel the history exuding from this place. We had breakfast in The Garden Court restaurant on several mornings; however, I found it hard to concentrate on the food. The restaurant space was breath-taking. Even if you do not stay at this hotel, you must visit just to see this. The check-in/check-out process was very easy and professional. All staff members that we encountered were very professional and friendly. We normally arrange private airport transportation; however, we chose to take BART on this trip. The trip was very easy. You board the train at the airport and exit at the hotel...the hotel entrance is across the street from the BART station. You never even have to change trains. If you love historic hotels with a prime location, modern amenties, plush rooms, and beautiful common areas, you will fall in love with this place. I have decided that The Palace Hotel is my new favorite hotel.	
