Aug 28 2008 	Excellent stay after initial problems	When you arrive at a hotel after travelling halfway across the world with 2 children, you need to have everything as it was requested. Therefore, as a desk clerk, when you tell a tired and sweaty 40 something dad that there is only one double queen room available on one floor and the other on another floor, and not the two adjoining king/queen rooms booked, you are taking your life in your hands. This particular dad expressed his dissatisfaction in no uncertain terms. Th clerk placed the blame squarely on the travel company's shoulders for not making things clear. I produced the travel vouchers outlining what was booked and was advised that although we had requested adjoining rooms (several weeks before) this was not guaranteed. Therefore we were faced with a stark choice. Our children of 9 and 11 on a separate floor (unthinkable) or myself and my wife on separate floors with a child each...hardly the perfect start to the dream luxury holiday we were promised. We opted for neither and all bunked in together on the 7th floor in an ok room. (We then had the same problem with Chinatown as a previous reviewer. we just walked there and looked for a restaurant. In the end we had just an 'average' meal). We were tired, but mostly we were disappointed with the first day. The next morning we set off for Alcatraz (highly recommended), but not before I had been to the desk to enquire about our prospects for an adjoining room for the next 2 nights. We were promised action would be taken and so it came to pass. That evening we were moved to the 4th floor and the rooms were excellent. A vast improvement. Things were looking up. The holiday took off from there. The pool at the Palace is great and very well maintained indeed. They offer free good quality coffee and juicy apples at both the pool and the front desk. There were free papers each day and the staff throughout were friendly and efficient. The concierge organised a great restaurant (Kuleto's on Powell) and were were treated with care and attention throughout. We finished our stay with breakfast in the Garden Room, and this was very pleasant and a beautiful setting. We never found time to eat in the hotel restaurants, although I didn't think Maxfields looked very child-friendly and so that was probably best. All in all, we really enjoyed the Palace despite the false start. Perhaps the nicest part was when I was checking out. At the front desk was the same clerk who had checked us in on the night we arrived. He couldn't have been more gracious and apologetic. I know these people are trained to make you feel better (or should be) but he certainly succeeded. They say the English are rubbish at complaining - well I gave him both barrels on that first night and yet he had the decency to tell me that he would have done the same and that I was within my rights to be unhappy. He sounded very sincere and seemed genuinely concerned to know that things had later improved. I left the Palace a happy man and will certainly return when I'm next in San Francisco...which i certainly hope I will be one day - it's a great city!	
