Aug 5 2008 	Old World charm; good service; clean if a little spartan rooms.	I stayed at the Palace Hotel in San Francisco in early August to attend a wedding. I was pleased to see that while it maintains its Old World, European charm and classiness, it has not become outdated or musty (which cannot be said about a few of SF's other old hotels). Before my stay I'd read about the historic hotel, how it goes back to 1875, was gutted by the 1906 quake/fire and then restored to its regal elegance; about how it hosted celebrities and world leaders, even hosting a gala to celebrate the creation of the United Nations. The hotel appeared to fit the description of a &quot;grand dame&quot;. My concern, however, was how it was going to stack up as a luxury hotel with the &quot;Luxury Collection&quot; brand that Starwood Hotels uses for its top-tier hotels. The visit was positive.Upon arrival, we used our Starwood Preferred Guest status to upgrade the room. Since we had friends in the hotel, a comparison of rooms revealed that our upgraded room was larger in sq. footage, but had no additional furniture or visible perks. The room, like all the others, had very high ceilings (a plus for the claustrophobic) and a European character. Our room faced busy Market Street, but the room air conditioner was able to drown it out fairly well. The furniture didn't include too many places to set things down, and the closet was average. The bathroom was a bit of a disappointment, it didn't have very much counter space, had below-average ventilation (not catastrophic, but not good), and the sink's tap appeared to need an upgrade to something more modern (i.e. something that wouldn't spurt water everywhere). The shower was good. There was a nice, large flat screen TV in the bedroom. The breakfast buffet was very good; its pricey (no surprise), but the quality of food is very good and the service was attentive. The overall hotel service was good. The highlight of the hotel is the lobby, in particular the exceptional Garden Room that hosts breakfast, an evening bar and can be rented out for special events (the wedding had its reception here). Many tourists stop by just to take a photo of it. The entire hotel benefits from light colors and skylights that bring in a surprising amount of light for a building of its vintage. Location can be important for any hotel, particularly one in a city with as tough a parking issue as San Francisco. In this aspect the Palace Hotel is well off. We were able to land at SFO, hop on the BART (subway) and get in front of the hotel in short order (there is a station directly in front of the hotel). The MUNI (street car) also stops right in front of the hotel on Market Street, and its only a few blocks from the Moscone Convention Center, MOMA and Union Square/Cable Cars. The Financial District is also close by. Definitely nothing to complain about here.The Palace Hotel is an above average hotel with adequate-but-not-outstanding rooms but enough charm and convenience to carry itself and satisfy most.	
Aug 5 2008 	Nice Hotel 	Alot of choices for hotels for our first visit to San Francisco so I was a bit overwhelmed when deciding where my husband and I should stay. Most rates were about the same but then I stumbled upon a $142/night pre-pay special on The Palace Hotel's website and I was sold since most of the places I had checked were between $200-$250.We couldn't have been more pleased with our choice! I did read some of the reviews about the thin walls and noise so I came prepared with ear plugs in case I needed them (I'm a light sleeper.) We could hear our neighbors on occasion although it was kind of muffled and it was never at a time when we wanted to sleep so I never had to use the ear plugs.We had a room on the 8th floor - no view since it was an interior room but it was nice to not have any street noise. The rooms were on the small side (it's an older hotel but with updates) but very well appointed with nice furniture, flat panel TV, comfy bed, etc. so not a big deal.They have free coffee and apples available daily in the check-in area.We had drinks at the bar a couple of times - good service and drinks.The doormen were great with the luggage and with some directions when we were looking for something in particular. In fact, everyone we encountered there (front desk, etc.) were very nice and accommodating. We told them we were celebrating an anniversary and when we checked into our room there was a plate of chocolate covered strawberries and a lovely note from the manager to start our celebration off just right!Loved the items in the glass cases along the main corridor which were from the hotel back in the 1920's (old menus, photos, etc.)The location was perfect - right across the street from BART, the F Line Streetcar (which will take you to the Ferry Bldg and Fisherman's Wharf), and a number of buses. We went to the muni station and purchased a 3 day muni pass so we could use anything and everything (except for BART) with the pass.We would definitely stay at The Palace Hotel again!	
Aug 4 2008 	Great Hotel	We Stayed here for 4 nights on the 5th floor, we didnt have a view but we didnt mind as we got a good night sleep, the bed was so comfy, the room was big. we had no problems with thin walls!! All the staff we came in to contact with were very nice and helpful.The hotel close to shops and buses never far away from anythingThe breakfast was good but at $28 a little over priced so only went in once.Stay here i'm sure you will love just like we did.	
Aug 1 2008 	Wonderful Hotel	My husband and I spent one night at the Palace, July 26th, as part of our anniversary weekend. We only had about a week to plan and hotels were scarce. I always comparison shop and rooms were coming up in the $250 range with no extra amenities. I was surprised when I found it for $179 through AAA. I called to be sure the rate was correct and it was! We stayed in room 791 with a king bed. We paid for the smallest room and we were upgraded to the next size. The room was beautiful and spacious. We were in an interior room, so there was no view. I didn't care. There was no street noise at night, so I slept like a baby, which is rare for me in a hotel. We always adjust the room temp, but for some reason, it was very comfortable, and we never changed it. The bathroom was large and there was wonderful pressure in the shower. For once, I left all my own things at home, shampoo, hairdryer, etc. All of their products were fine for one night. Having read that the walls were paper thin, we kind of braced ourselves when one of our neighbors returned to their room next door about 9:30 pm. They laughed and talked, which was easy to hear. By 9:40, no noise. It stayed that way the rest of the night. We had a drink at the bar. One glass of wine and a bourbon on the rocks was around $13 plus tip. We did have breakfast on Sunday morning, $28 per person. It's a bit much, but there were plenty of choices, we both went back for seconds. The brunch was starting soon. It was much more expensive, no need to spend that much money! Plus, the room is like dining with the queen! Dinner on Saturday night was at the Daily Grill on Geary, just past Macy's. Great place, mostly tourists, but we've eaten there before and the food was good every time. Friendly wait staff is a bonus.One of my favorite parts of the stay was going for a swim at 7 am on Sunday morning. The pool is on the 4th floor under a glass dome. There were a few others who came and went while we were there, but it was a very relaxing swim for an hour. The hot tub was closed for maintenance. I don't like to use public hot tubs, so no great loss there. The gym was very busy by 7. I would say there were at least 7 or 8 by the time we left the pool. The pool is traditional chlorination. I am used to saltwater pools now, so the smell was a bit strong and the water did sting our eyes. But for one hour it wasn't a big deal. We parked behind the hotel at the Hearst Parking Center. The address is 45 Third Street. The rate was $20 for 24 hours. That's a great price, the hotel charges $48. One important fact to consider. The garage we used is not open 24 hours. Sundays, it is open from 10 to 10. If you have to be out early, don't park there, you'll never get out! None of the rest of the week is 24 hours, either, so you will want to check their times. But the $28 savings over the hotel parking basically paid for one breakfast. If you have a chance, go to the De Young Museum in Golden Gate Park and see the Chihuly Glass Exhibit. It ends in September, but it's magnificent! If you bring a camera, you can't use a flash. My Nikon worked fine without the flash, but about a third of the pictures were blurry. I have a pretty steady hand usually, but I am happy with the rest of the pics. We also walked over to the Conservatory of Flowers in the park. Just wonderful there, but very humid inside for the tropical plants.On Sunday, we went to AT&amp;T park to watch the Giants. Parking was $30! We parked in one of the ferry buildings. Amici's Pizza, across the street from the park is great East Coast pizza. All in all, I would stay at the Palace again. The price was great for San Francisco. It felt very relaxed, no stuffiness from the staff and a perfect location for Union Square. I will take my daughters there in December for our (almost) annual window shopping trip. They will love it!	
Jul 31 2008 	Handy location	The Palace hotel is a nice hotel. The lobby is very impressive, check-in went smoothly. Our room was a decent size with traditional decor but the view was really disappointing. Our room looked out onto 2 brick walls which was a shame as it was our first time in San Francisco. We arrived from the airport on the BART and the hotel couldn't have been handier. It was well placed for shops, trams, ferry building, union square, etc.The walls are as thin as the other reviews say though.. I didn't sleep very well any of the 3 nights we were in the Palace; the people in the room next door weren't talking particularly loudly but they did talk til after 2am and had the tv on.The pool area looked nice, although we didn't use it as we were happy being out and about sight-seeing.	
Jul 21 2008 	Solid 4.5 but thin walls	My wife and I stayed at the Palace for three nights, having driven up in our rental car from Santa Cruz. I booked the room on Hotwire and got a great deal--a huge room with king bed for 150 dollars a night plus tax. The lobby and first floor of the hotel are remarkably beautiful, and our room was very nicely appointed in terms of linens, towels, furniture, etc. Beautiful vintage solid brass hardware on the door of the room, monogrammed, etc. Very nice. We did not demand much of the staff but our experience was with them was just fine, nor did we use the beautiful pool, much to our regret. Others have commented on the very thin walls and it is true--and weird for a hotel of this caliber. Bring your earplugs or sleep with a pillow over your head if the guy in the next room has a cough. A couple of things you should know: they charge for internet in the room (still!) but there is free wi-fi in the lobby. A small biz computer in the lobby is for printing out boarding passes and not for e-mail. Otherwise checking your e-mail in the business center will cost you 5. 25 min. charge (please). The hotel is in the middle of the biz district so night time there is dead, but three blocks aways is Union Square, and a few more in the opposite direction is the Embarcadero. Better location imho than Nob Hill etc. Re. coffee in the a.m. they supply it in the lobby and it is fine. We did not check out the bar or restaurant because there are so many within walking distance. Less than a block to to the right as you exit the hotel is a Starbucks if you need latte (which we do). Parking by the hotel is 50 bucks per night (highway robbery) but they will tell you that right around the corner on the same block are two garages where you can park for 20 dollars a night--fine for a big city and plenty convenient. Very easy walking distance (2 blocks) to SFMoMa (and other museums such as the Jewish Contemporary) and the Yerba Buena Arts Center. Be sure to grab dinner at The Slanted Door at the Ferry Bldg. on the Embarcadero. You can walk there (and make your rez online, early). Would I stay there again? Sure, but keep in mind the thin wall problem. Everything else was 4.5 in my book.	
Jul 15 2008 	Don't Trust the Palace to Honor Reservation -- Even for Gold Starwood Member	Booked ahead through American Express travel. Hotel advised me when I arrived that they were oversold -- that a larger than expected number of guests did not leave as expected. Upshot for me was not being able to stay in the hotel I had reserved. Hotel sent me to the nearby St. Regis, which is Starwood's luxury brand but whose rooms are nowhere near as charming as the Palace. After being agitated at midnight (after a seven-hour flight from JFK) when the room wasn't ready, I had a sleepless night at the St. Regis -- windows could not be opened, annoying remote electronic control device glowed brightly all night, AC blew right over the bed, room lacked iron/ironing board, toilet ran all night, privacy deadbolt wouldn't engage. I had to go back to the Palace for breakfast, and a room still was not ready by 10 a.m. My morning change of clothes was in the hotel's bathroom. Recommendations for Palace:-- When you oversell, call the customer to alert them of the situation so they don't show up and get disappointed-- When you send someone to another hotel because you have oversold the Palace, make sure the new hotel can accommodate the guest for his/her entire stay (so the guest is not inconvenienced by having to repack and return to the Palace)-- Have the room cleaners come in early on mornings when re-routed guests are coming back to check in. I am sure the rooms vacated by early leavers could have been cleaned by 10 a.m.-- Delight those who have been bumped with ample Starwood points, or a dinner in the hotel restaurant, or both, so they understand that management is apologetic. (Nothing was offered until I asked)Despite using a Starwood Preferred Guest American Express card, booking the room with Amex Travel, and being a Starwood Gold member for years, the Palace really let me down.I am a swimmer and have used the Palace lap pool for many years. Now I'm on the hunt for a new SF pool and hotel.	
