May 21 2008 	Great business hotel	I was in San Francisco for a business conference at another hotel a few blocks away. Generally I stay where a conference is being held, but there were no rooms available, and the booking agent put me in contact with the Palace. I was so glad she did! My hotel experience for the three days I was there was outstanding. My husband and child joined me, and she was treated like a little princess by the hotel staff.Because I was booking for business, the view and size of the room were not very important, so I got the smallest room with a king sized bed. There wasn't really much choice available, as the whole town was packed. Even though the room was truly tiny, it was appointed with a decent sized television, a very comfortable queen anne chair with footstool, an end table and a desk. There was room enough for a crib beside the bed as well. When I booked, the agent was very apologetic about the size of the room I would be getting, explaining the room in detail. Frankly, she made it seem much worse than it was. The bedding was luxurious with a gold embroidered quilt, navy throw, soft sheets, and duvet. (FYI, this is the &quot;Heavenly Bed&quot;, but with the added luxe comforter on top of the duvet. The crib was appointed with a soft blanket, which you don't usually get at all in most hotels. The carpeting was clean and ornate. The bathroom was small, and when I booked, the booking agent informed me that I would not have a tub, but only a shower. Because I was traveling on business last minute, even though my family accompanied, I didn't mind. Frankly, I just needed a room somewhere in San Francisco close enough to the conference, so I wasn't picky. However, when we got to the room, there was a small tub, oddly shaped to fit the small space, and enough to bathe a child. It had the same tile and marble vanity as the other rooms, just a tiny tub/shower, enclosed in glass.We ordered room service the night we arrived, just dessert and fresh fruit, but it was prompt and tasty. We took advantage of the breakfast buffet spread in the giant part of the lobby, and it was fabulous. The wait staff was courteous, we never wanted for coffee, and the french toast was tasty.The front desk attendants and concierge were helpful in giving me directions to my conference and in helping my husband find the places he wanted to visit during the days. The bellmen were nice, as were the valets. They helped with everything, and with a smile.The Wall Street Journal is stocked in the Mezzanine elevator lobby, and can be brought to your room if wanted, so there's more than just the crappy USA Today you see at most biz hotels.I highly recommend Kyo Ya, the Japanese restaurant. We had sushi and sashimi, and the inventive rolls, albeit not really authentic Japanese, were out of this world. The sushi is absolutely on par with the best places in Tokyo. Better than most places in Tokyo, actually. We didn't go for the Kaiseki set dinners, so I can't comment on how good they are, but given how good the sushi is, I would venture that if you have a little extra money burning a hole in your pocket, you'll be happy with the food.	
