Jan 26 2008	Beautiful Common Areas but Room Details Lacking	The Palace Hotel has beautiful and grand common areas. The staircase is marvelous with the original granite steps and ornate balustrade. Each day I walked up and down these stairs to enjoy their timeless beauty - and also to warm up from the drafty room. There is a spectacular atrium room for breakfast, lunch and tea. Be sure to bring your credit card though, because &quot;Tea for Two&quot; is about $100. The room had nice high ceilings, great crown moldings, cornices, etc. The room was simply and tastefully decorated. It contained a king bed, chair with ottoman, desk, bench, large flat screen TV, frig and iron. There were spots on the duvet cover and carpet. The mattress was too a little too firm, pillows were lackluster. A DVD player would have made a nice addition.The bathroom was small with insufficient counter space. A magnifying mirror and hair dryer were included. The shower head was great. Toiletries included uninspiring shampoo, conditioner, lotion, shower gel, and bar soap. The bathroom exhaust vent ran constantly and could not be turned off - it was not connected to any light switch. Not only was the noise from this annoying, but it made for very drafty bath time. The bathroom floor came complete with black hairs about 5 inches long which were not removed during this stay.Bottled water was replenished - that was nice. Evening turn-down came with a sweet. Apples were complimentary at the front desk all day, and good coffee there in the morning.I believe the thermostat was pretend. No matter how high the temperature was set, the room never became warm. The fan could not be turned off - just adjusted low, medium or high. The room was very drafty, and since the weather outside was rainy and cold, it made it impossible to ever get warm. There was a gap between the window and the frame of about a half inch, so a breeze came through there, along with all the street noise. It sounded like the sirens were right at the window on the 6th floor. There were nice heavy drapes that could be closed - but who wants the room dark during daylight hours??? Drafts also came from around the door frame.There was no soundproofing whatsoever. I was privy to every word spoken and every other &quot;activity&quot; of the neighboring room. I even knew when a throat was cleared. Which means, of course, that they were privy to everything going on in my room. Upon arrival, the lamp plug was broken off - and was sitting several feet from where it would be plugged in - meaning it was obvious to housekeeping - yet it was left that way for me. This lack of attention to detail carried through the stay. There was no room service menu in the room - one had to be requested to be sent up. There was a rusty metal panel on the bathroom ceiling that steam would condense on, and then drip rusty brown water onto the toilet seat - creating a somewhat unpleasant image.Internet was $17/day and parking a shocking $50/night. Yikes!! A room service hamburger and beverage came to about $30 delivered.The Palace location is surrounded by lots of shopping and dining. Walking distance to Chinatown, the Ferry, etc. Pay attention to where you're walking though, as a few blocks in the wrong direction can certainly change the tone quickly to something disconcerting.Overall impression is the Palace is a beautiful hotel. If they'd just pay attention to the details, it could be a fabulous experience, instead of just average.	
