Aug 6 2007	Hit and Miss in San Francisco	We stayed at the Palace Hotel in mid July 2007. We did a fair bit of homework before booking, via Trip Advisor and other sources, but no hotels in San Francisco seem to be perfect. We excluded a few due to ongoing refurbishment works, eventually we figured that Starwood are usually a safe bet and seemed to have a good price. Originally we had asked for a high floor suite but got allocated a suite on the third floor as that was all they had available. We had chosen the Palace in part because it had a pool for our daughter, which is on the 4th floor. It turned out that being able to walk to the pool up a single flight of stairs right outside the room was very convenient. The pool was usually quiet with a few other kids in it. The changing rooms were a bit basic and did not offer the usual spa-style luxuries you might expect. There is no life guard nor, it would appear, any rules or restrictions. The two room suite was not exactly the most luxurious we have ever stayed in and was looking tired and old fashioned. Flat screen TVs and computers haven’t made it to San Francisco yet. The rooms were small and the two double beds quite cramped in the bedroom. They were also bit soft for our taste, not the usual Starwood “heavenly beds”, but at $900 for 3 nights the suites were fairly priced. The bathroom was very small with an over bath shower only. Large wardrobes, safe and minibar were available but no tea or coffee making facilities and you have to pay $17 a day for internet access which is ridiculous when you can get it for free at MacDonald’s down the road! The room was quite noisy with thin walls, rattley air-con and traffic and building work early morning, so take your ear plugs. We had expected more of this hotel both in service and quality. For example, on arrival we had asked housekeeping for extra robes, a missing hotel services directory and few other things. I wonder if they have arrived yet? Another bizarre thing was turndown at 5pm some days!The hotel is well situated for Union Square and shopping access and for trams and buses. The doorman was helpful but most of the staff we encountered were indifferent and there was a constant queue for the concierge. Eventually we only used her to order a car to the airport and she got that wrong. The Garden room is pretty but only open for lunch and breakfast. You would think they could open part of it as a lounge in the evenings. We had lunch here and the food was very good, however the waiting staff were totally forgetful and disorganised and got our orders mixed up, leaving us with the wrong meal. We tried the Japanese restaurant in the hotel which was nice enough though not spectacular. The “famous” Pied Piper bar is very busy and noisy but there aren’t any other lounges to relax in for a drink and a game.	
