Jul 25 2007	Wonderful stay at Palace	I stayed at the Palace Hotel from July3-7, 2007, and I thought it wasa wonderful hotel. I got an AAA special rate of $159. per night for adeluxe, preferred room. The offer included a room upgrade if available. As far as I know I did not receive an upgrade. My room was elegant and I thought it and the bathroom were big (maybe that isbecause I often stay in Marriott and Hilton properties.). I was really pleased to find that the bathroom had a window. I was on the 6th floor in an inside room and everything was very quiet. It was hard for me to realize I was in the middle of a busy, noisy city. I was a little hesitant about staying here because of the comments on Tripadvisor about thin walls. Once or twice, I heard water running either in the room next door or perhaps upstairs. And once or twice I heard someone in the hall. But those are noises I expect to hear in any hotel. None of these noises were loud. I really wondered if anyone were in the rooms next to me. So one morning when I left my room, I checked and found “Privacy Please” signs on the doors of both rooms on either side of me. I found all the hotel staff from the bellmen to the desk clerks to the maids and even the concierge to be friendly and cordial. One day when I was leaving my room, a maid was coming out into the hall from a room she was cleaning to get supplies. She not only acknowledged me but asked me how I was doing. She seemed ready to engage in conversation if I had encouragedit. The concierge were wonderful and knowledgeable. They were busy every time I passed by. But when I actually stopped to get information from one of them, she acted like I was the most importantperson she had to wait on that day. One day after breakfast, I asked one of the restaurant employees a question about the hotel history. She did not know the answer to my question and suggested that I might check with an employee in the lobby area. I went on my way and was admiring furniture and fixtures. I looked up and saw the restaurant employee. She had asked one of her fellow employees and then she looked for me until she found me and gave me my answer.I thought the bed was very nice. I probably would have preferred that the mattress be a tiny bit more firm, but I thought it was a moderate level between soft and firm and I had no problem with it. I was glad to find that there was an alarm clock in the room by the bed. However, I did not use it except to see what time it was. I used the wake-up service the mornings I needed to be up by a certain time. And that service was great. In other hotels, I have found that such a service is sometime early or late in calling. At the Palace, it was “right on time”.The hotel public areas were luxurious. As others have mentioned, the hotel is in an excellent area for public transportation. I used BART and the MUNI and walked a lot of places. I enjoyed having a small refrigerator in my room and it was easy to walk to Bristol Farms (grocery store) in San Francisco Center to get a few things to put in the refrigerator. I took BART back to the hotel because I didn’t want to walk back with my groceries. Walgreen’s was also a couple of blocks away.There were homeless people around but for the most part they kept to themselves and did not bother anyone on walking on the street. I found the area safe, even after dark. One night I went to a play at the Curran Theatre and walked the 5-6 blocks there and back, coming back around 11:00.a.m. The first few blocks were crowded with people, but by the last few, everyone had disappeared.I did not have a car so I did not have to pay for parking. I did not have a computer with me, so I didn’t have to worry about connections and fees.I would consider staying at the Palace again. And I would consider it even if the rate were around $200 a night. That seems to be the rate in a lot of hotels in San Francisco. And I really liked the areaand the room. For this trip I was considering several other hotels. Most of them would have cost more than the Palace and I doubt if any of them would have been as nice. Regarding the negative comments about the Palace Hotel (or any other hotel), I think a lot of them could be avoided if people would check out hotel websites to get information and call the hotel to ask questions. Then perhaps there would not be so many surprises. Some people might say that they don’t have time for that. I would say that is interesting because they sure have time to write negative comments and gripe about everything	
Jul 24 2007 	The Palace right for the price.	Stayed at The Palace and came away with no regrets. The hotel is centrally located on Market Street. About a 5 minute walk to Union Square or the business district of the Embarcadero. The staff was pleasant. The room we stayed in was large and more importantly clean. The gym was modern with about 8 aerobic machines along with free weights. The indoor pool looked inviting but was unable to take a dip. At a rate of 109.00, a night, purchased by calling Sheraton, it was a good deal. The only complaint is having to pay for internet access. If 'cheaper' chain motels can give you free internet access why can't a high end 'hotel' give you the same service. Definitely a consideration when going back to San Francisco.	
Jul 23 2007 	Nice Hotel just a bit boring	I returned to the Palace for a long business trip this July, the hotel is nice, its just not very exciting. The room I had was decent and the bed was very comfortable. The room faced Market, this became a problem several days into my trip, as construction started late at night. The front desk assisted me with a room change. The second room I received, inner room, was really dark and small. It would have been a bummer to have stayed in that room for seven nights; however, it was quiet and I was only in the room for two nights. The photos in the review are of the first room facing Market. The gym is average to below average. The cardio equipment is really old. The pool area is nice. As for the concierge, two of the female staff members were really rude. One gentleman who worked the concierge desk gave some great advice... however, stay away from the female staff. They were mean, rude, and never smiled once. If you like old grand hotels and you intend to spend a fair amount of time in the lobby, this is the place for you. If you want a flat screen TV, free internet service in the lobby, nice cardio equipment, or a friendly concierge... go elsewhere. Its nice, its just not great. I would only stay here again for my starwood points... but the W is down the street as well as the new Westin!	
Jul 19 2007 	Great location to cable cars streetcars BART	Stayed three nights at Palace using reward points. Was a little concerned about some of the less than stellar reviews. Well, we were VERY pleased with the Palace. The public areas are beautiful. We got a slight upgrade to a larger two double bed room so we could better fit a rollaway. The rooms were well maintained with nice bathrooms. Wide, majestic hallways. The Montgomery St. BART station is literally outside the door of the hotel - very convenient if you fly in via SFO or OAK. The streetcar stops outside (to take you to Alcatraz pier/Fisherman's Wharf, etc). And the cable car station is a few blocks away. TIP: Don't queue up at the end of the cable car line (it could be a huge line) - go down a block or two on the cable car route and wait for the cable car to come to you (they don't totally fill them up at the end station). YOU HAVE TO BE SOMEWHAT AGGRESSIVE if you want to wedge your way into cars that may appear to be full. Check first to see if the car has any open spots on the running boards (BEST place to ride, hanging on to the rails).Breakfast at the hotel was a kings' ransom - but there are literally dozens of places within seconds of the hotel for breakfast. That's your better bet.	
Jul 19 2007 	Location and Charm!	My husband, 4 year-old-daughter, and I stayed in a superior room (#406) July 3-8 for an AAA rate of $129 a night. We were pleased with the location and most of the services but would not spend over $200 a night for them. As mentioned in previous posts, the location is awesome, especially if you are intending to use public transportation. The BART station and streetcar stops are right there. We either walked or took public transportation to all our activities in San Francisco. The area felt as safe as a city area could feel at all times. There were always homeless people visible on Market, but they did not disturb us.  Our room faced the entrance of the hotel; some noise was heard from the hallways (mainly in the morning and early evening), but not from the street. The noise did not interrupt our sleep. We thought the room was simply but nicely appointed. The mini refrigerator in the room was appreciated. Two bathrobes hung in the closet and bottled water was left each day. The pool was wonderful and relaxing, and the staff at the desk there were helpful. The check-in desk was often busy, but the wait was never more than five minutes. The concierge was extremely busy but was helpful enough; however, nothing recommended stuck out as being superb. One small irritation was the internet service. My husband never could get the wireless to work, and neither the front desk nor the business center they sent him to could help. In fact, the business center claimed they couldn’t help at all because they were completely separate from the service (why did the front desk send my husband there for help then?). After being frustrated with that, he paid for the wired connection in the room which was rather which also was a pain to use and slow. Since the hotel is charging $13.99 a day to use its internet services, you’d think it would be more helpful and up-to-date. All in all, we enjoyed our stay at the Palace and thought the rate we paid was a deal for what we got!	
