Oct 30 2006 	Exceptional service at the Palace	I recently stayed at the Palace hotel for a week. I needed to be there for a 4 day conference and my wife and I decided to come out early for some hanging out in San Francisco without kids. She returned once the conference started. I can say that my experience as a business traveler was excellent. As tourists, my wife and I thoroughly enjoyed ourselves. I have the good fortune to travel extensively and can say that the overall experience at the Palace was one of the best experiences I have had in a long time.First, the property is centrally located. We found it relatively easy to get around. Because it was blocks to Union Square, we found transportation easy to obtain and most things were close by. Second, we found the rooms to be spacious and well maintained. In fact it had one of the best showers I have ever experienced. The Pied Piper Bar was nice, but a bit overpriced (to be expected) and the famous Palm Court was as majestic and beautiful as I had read. The hotel is indeed historic which added something to the place. Interesting notes, President Warren Harding died at the hotel while President, other famous celebrities and world leaders have stayed at the Palace, and it played a role in The San Francisco earthquake in 1906 which all gave it some historical relevance. All that being said, it still felt like a modern hotel. There was just more to it than your usual Hilton, Hyatt, Marriott etc. It had a boutique hotel feel to it.More importantly, we found the service to be exceptional. Because I was both a business traveler and tourist I had a great opportunity to experience their service in different circumstances. I found the business service with packages to be prompt and well handled. As far as tourist goes, I found the concierge staff to be the best part of the entire experience. When we arrived I asked the bell man where we could obtain 2 Giants-Dodger tickets that afternoon (last game of the season). Within minutes, they had arranged 2 box seats reasonably priced for half the price I expected to pay. This experience was followed with 4 perfect recommendations for dinner and 2 recommended tours that were exceptional (one to Yosemite and the other of San Francisco). In each situation I felt the staff listened to what I was actually looking for and made a recommendation based upon what I wanted. I never felt that I was sent to a place they had a deal with or where they could just send tourists without giving it much thought. When I left they even arranged my car and driver to the airport which was almost the same cost as a taxi (it was their suggestion!! I didn't even ask and it was a nice Mercedes sedan). Of course I tipped appropriately for this good service. I usually scrutinize service at hotels to determine their value (although you should always be respectful of the people providing the service -- they are just doing their job). I was very impressed with everyone I encountered. I think this speaks highly of the management.I have stayed in other locations like the Fairmont and Mark Hopkins. After this trip I will stay or recommend the Palace when I am in San Francisco if the budget allows.	
Oct 10 2006 	Classic Beauty	I spent three lovely days at this historic hotel. The main public rooms were well decorated and the linens were top drawer. My large double room was comfortable, quiet, elegant and clean. The bathroom was spacious filled with high end personal sized toiletries.Maid service was efficient and timely.If you want the latest in electronic gizmos, then this is not the place. TV had just basic cable programs for free. I did not bring a laptop, so I cannot comment on internet connections.The concierges were all quite knowledgeable in local events, restaurants, shopping and touring.The location was perfect for shopping, Moscone Convention center, SFMOMA, and general touring. If you are taking limited baggage, the Montgomery Station of the BART is just outside of the hotel, making the trip from the airport in about 30 minutes, which interms of time and money , beats a taxi during rush hour.The only negative is that downtown is jammed with unfortunate beggars who are often aggressive, filthy, rude, intoxicated and persistent. You can hardly walk 1/2 block without getting accosted, and I am not talking about the Tenderloin area ,which should be off limits to anyone. Truly, this is a social problem of major proportions. Unfortunately many of the top hotels are here including the Four Seasons, W, Mariott, Hilton, Saint Francis, Clift, and many others. There is also a Ritz-Carlton going up across the street. I don't know how the city will deal with its homeless and social misfits. At night one can see gang members walking several abreast in the SOMA area. No, the police were not evident save for the foot of Powell Street and parts of the Union Square area.	
