Aug 15 2006	Lame hotel experience -- and overpriced!	I travel frequently to San Francisco on business and have sampled almost every luxury hotel in the city. Despite it's supposedly famous reputation, this one has consistently been very disappointing every time I have given it a try in the last five years.It's location is awkward -- no views, limited restaurants nearby, and popular with drunks and homeless at night. Furniture is frumpy, similar to the style you see in mom-and-pop bed-and-breakfasts. The hotel does not seem to have made the investment in super-beds that almost every other chain has. Alarm clock radio is a cheap model without MP3 connections. Television is small and old-style CRT, not flat-screen. Most galling is that the desk chairs are extremely low and cannot be adjusted. Seated in the chair, one meets the desk at shoulder height! You will need serious chiropractics to restore spine damage after working any amount of time at the workstation. Pretty unbelievable for a hotel that aspires to such prestige. Internet service is a whopping $16.00 per day and no different from what's offered typically for $9.95 or free at almost every other hotel. Rooms are very quiet because of thick, old walls, However, this is not the case if you have one of the many &quot;connector&quot; rooms. Tall ceilings give a grand and classy feel. Carpets are faded, making stains readily apparent. Bring slippers if you are finicky! About half of the rooms also have very ugly internal courtyard views of each other. Bathroom is nicely finished with generous marble. It is well-lit and has a nice vanity mirror. However, tubs still have old-style shower curtains that leave you little room to avoid touching the filthy things.Public areas are quite plush with old-style charm and grandeur. Health club has very dated equipment -- and there is an additional charge! Members of Starwood's elite programs, used to the standard club lounge offering complimentary hors d'oeuvres and breakfast, will be deeply disappointed to find out that this hotel has none.Check out time for this hotel -- highlighted in a special card within the check-in package -- is 11 am unlike most other San Francisco hotels which have noon or 1pm.Overall something is just not quite right with this hotel. I always feel a bit let down for the price and reputation. I think this is because there is just excessive nickel-and-diming at the hotel; outrageous charges for things that are free and standard courtesy at almost every other hotels, including the Starwood chain. In the end, the overall experience feels closer to what one would expect of Four Points rather than the supposedly crown-jewel Luxury Collection. Incidentally, This hotel was once a Four Seasons or Ritz-Carlton, but stripped of that affiliation when it failed to meet standards. I'm not sure this underperforming hotel even meets Luxury Collection standards.	
