May 4 2006 	Caruso still carousing in the corridors	Stayed at the Palace for a convention in April 2006. It is just a few blocks from the Moscone Center, and pleasantly situated for a stroll to the shops around Union Square, or to take the Powell line Cable Car halfway to the stars up Nob Hill. (Don't miss the stained glass in Grace Cathedral up on California St in Nob Hill, by the way!) The Palace room was comfortable and clean, and the staff were helpful. Being a conventioneer, I always dined elsewhere, so cannot comment on the food. At night however there were some singing patrons who strolled the corridors at 1-2am going back to their rooms (I guess) - perhaps I even heard strains of the great Enrico Caruso (who was staying at the Palace when the 1906 Earthquake struck). Neverthless, I could have done with the sleep! This time, I didn't try the hotel pool - but was impressed with it last time I stayed here a few years back.	
Apr 27 2006	The lore of history	This famous hotel, which succumbed to the firestorms of the 1906 earthquake, is opulent and ideally situated. We chose this hotel mainly for its history and to catch a glimpse into the gilded age. We reserved a room for fours days after bumping into a drastically reduced hotel rate for booking online and selecting only bed size as a preference. Upon checking in, we learned that only smoking rooms were available, but the room could be refreshed if needed. We had a standard room on the seventh floor and were able to air it out by opening a window. The high ceilings throughout the Palace add to the overall atmosphere of being in an historic building. As noted by previous posters, our room was well furnished and the public areas are truly magnificent. For us history buffs, I wish the hotel aired a documentary on its illustrious past. We eat two meals at the Palace. We had breakfast in the rococo Garden Court restaurant. Although expensive, our bill came to $60, the buffet was plentifully and good. The restaurant certainly pushes its breakfast buffet as our waiter only mentioned it. Later, we heard someone asking for the menu. We had dinner at Maxfield's Piped Piper. The food was delicious and the atmosphere prefect.Our only problem occurred at 2 am when two people went down the hall yelling nonsense sounds. They were deliberately trying to wake people up and they succeeded. This stunt surprised us. It was more fitting for a college dorm then an upscale hotel. The Palace is pricey, and there are other comparable accommodations at cheaper rates. However, splurge on staying at the Palace for its beauty, history, and overall high quality, especially if you find a discounted rate.	
