Feb 14 2005	best combination of quality and convenience in the city	I have stayed at the Palace multiple times, and each time I have found it to be perfectly fine. The location is by far the best of any hotel in San Francisco, on Market Street right next to the Montgomery BART station. My room was quiet, comfortable, clean, and perfectly big enough. The shower is excellent. The lobby is cool. There are free newspapers. The people were all fine. And it was all remarkably cheap, booked through Expedia.The only glitch I experienced was that the electrical power shut down in that part of San Francisco (the whole neighborhood, not just the hotel) for quite a few hours one evening and most of the night. For a while the elevators weren't operating and I had to climb the stairs. As far as I was concerned the hotel dealt with this fine. For example they handed out glowsticks.	
Feb 2 2005	Grand common areas; not-so-grand rooms	Pros: Central location, amazing lobby and common areas. Beds were very comfortable and the rooms were clean. Our room was quiet although we were not facing the street (instead, we had an unappealing view of a brick wall).Cons: Rooms were small but the tall ceilings made for a less claustrophobic feeling. Because the rooms were small, there was no buffer space between the door and the bed so you could easily hear what was going on in the hallway. This could be a problem if you happened to get noisy neighbors but all we heard was the occasional door closing (I guess we avoided any street noise with the aforementioned brick wall-view room). The bathrooms were also very small; it barely fit two people and there was no tub. Room service menu had price discrepancies between the All-Day Menu and the Late-Night Menu. When we called room service and alerted them to the price difference, they said they mentioned it to the manager before but nothing has been done to fix it.If you care more about the room than the lobby/common areas, you can get a better deal at the Omni.	
Jan 12 2005	Pretty Good -- when someone else is paying	Stayed here Jan. 8-9, 2005. Agree with other users that the entry/foyer/lobby is amazing. Really beautiful. Got a room on the third floor. This was a business trip, so paid for by company. Our room was lovely -- high ceilings, nicely decorated. But our view -- if you could call it that -- was of the roof. The bathroom floor looked like it hadn't been mopped in ages. And the room was excessively noisy -- my poor friend was awake all night from the sounds of the sirens and doors slamming in the hallway. Company catered party (food by palace hotel). Food was average -- very much typical hotel food. Warmed-over in chafing dishes, pretty bad. I would have been furious to pay the $229 a night they charged the company, but as it was free to me i couldn't really complain. I'd say if you can get a good deal here ($150 a night or so) by all means go for it. Good location.	
Jan 7 2005	The Palace was Spectacular	We spent two nights at the Palace Hotel and we loved it! The hotel is so beautiful and historic. The rooms were very nice and the beds were wonderful - heavenly - we slept like logs! We had a nice quiet room on the 8th floor along Montgomery St. The employees treated us like royalty, and the concierge service was terrific. It's in a great location near the financial district, Union square, shopping, and Chinatown. We didn't order room service or eat at the restaurant, though it looked very inviting. (The Sunday brunch was $65 per person, too rich for us.) We ate at a lot of great restaurants and took the Alcatraz tour and a coach bus tour of the city. We would love to return to the Palace and San Francisco.	
Jan 6 2005	Good experience fine room	Stayed there in December 2004 for one night when we arrived in S.F. earlier than expected. Found the room on Expedia and paid &lt;$150 for a king room. A very good bargain. The room was small-ish, but to be expected in a large city. High ceilings, very comfortable bed, overall clean. Decent bathroom but nothing extravagant. The hotel lobby and common spaces were more grand, and the indoor pool, hot-tub, and fitness center (a bit small, but adequate), were really well-utilized by us. The parking at $40 was too high, but there seemed to be no other easy choice. All in all, a good deal it seemed and a good overall experience. Would definitely stay there again, especially for the price.	
Dec 31 2004	Totally Positive Experience	We stayed Christmas night at the Palace rather than traveling back to Sonoma County where we live. Yes, the rooms are on the small side (this is an old, though totally elegant, hotel) and ours was tastefully furnished. I'd requested, and received, a quiet room, having read about someone's unpleasant experience where their room faced Market Street (this, I agree, might have been unpleasant). Our room was also on the same floor as the pool and spa (also requested and received). We did have room service, a quick pizza and salad before going to a party, and found the service prompt, the food and price also satisfactory. The spa and pool attendant was gracious, as was each employee with whom we came in contact. My only complaint would be that the pool needed additional water - the water level was low. But it was indoors (many California hotel pools have outside pools, if they have them at all) and I thoroughly enjoyed the swim, sauna and jacuzzi.Yes, the parking is another $40 plus tips. This is the heart of the City, and the parking garage around the corner would have been about the same for the time period we stayed. I must report that ours was a thoroughly positive experience, and we would return to the Palace.	
Dec 27 2004	Sheraton Palace: Location good the rest so-so	We just returned from a four-night stay at The Palace. All in all, it was nice but there certainly is room for improvement. The best thing about the hotel is its location—near the SFMOMA, Bart (in fact there is a station at the corner that allows you to easily go to and from the airport), Ferry Plaza Terminal, Chinatown, etc.. The health club and exercise room is also nice with a wonderful and welcoming staff. I found the concierge somewhat lacking, perhaps because she had way too much on her plate. She knew nothing about holiday restaurant hours in the hotel and wasn’t all that well versed on good dining options near the hotel. Agree that parking is over the top at $40 per day. That does not include the gratuity you give the valet each time you get your car. The rooms are OK, but for a deluxe room, it was on the small side with lamps awkwardly positioned around the room. It was difficult to walk around the room without crashing into the lamps. The bathroom was on the small side.I’d stay here again because of the location and the health club. I wouldn’t spend a dime on hotel food with so many options within walking distance.	
