Dec 18 2004	The palace is awesome	I have lived in the bay area for 25 years and stay in SF hotels all the time. I am partial to the Monaco and Campton Place. I have stayed at all relevant hotels, the St. Francis, the Fairmont, The Ritz.I have always wanted to stay at the Palace, but just never have. Me and my wife stayed there Friday to finish our Christmas shopping. The location has improved dramitically. The public areas of this hotel are unparralled. The Garden Court has got to be one of the most beautiful dining areas in the world. The Pied Piper has a huge Maxfield Parrish original behind the bar tha must be worth 2-3 million. There is slab marble everywhere. It is truly awesome for an american hotel.Our room was very inexpensive $139, and was great. It was large, the bed was great, the furniture was actually pretty nice for a hotel and the details were awesome. The ceilings are coved and 14 feet tall. It has been remodeled recently and is very clean and up to date. The service is very good.In addition this hotel has hosted JFK, Oscar Wilde, royalty from around the world, really almost everyone of interest from 1870 to 1970. It is pretty cool.I had read the reviews on this website and was really surprised it is as special as it is. If you appreciate the great architecture of the US you have to stay here. Really nothing bad to say, other than the parking, room service, etc, does increase your cost a bit, but who cares at $135 for THE PALACE.	
Dec 11 2004 	Palace - not really a "palace"	My wife and I recently stayed five nights at the Palace in SF. The foyer, restaurants and common areas were quite gourgeous and well-appointed. The individual rooms were satisfactory - paint was peeling from the ceiling, carpet was not clean in several locations in the room, and charges for additional items like ethernet connection ($!5.99/day), fax receipt ($5) and (even) toll free calls ($2/each) were outlandish on top of a &quot;discounted&quot; room rate of $300/day (including taxes).A requested wake up call was 30 minutes late and I was not notified of an incoming fax. The bright spot of the stay was the responsive, politie and helpful concierge staff; particularly Debbie Lew.Would I stay there again when in San Francisco? No.	
Dec 6 2004	Old World Charm	For a place to crash after a christmas party last weekend, I turned to Expedia for help. In about 2 minutes, I found a king non-smoking room at the Palace Hotel for $129. I was a little wary of what to expect after reading some of the reviews posted here, but overall, I think it is definitely a wonderful hotel in a great part of the city. There were some things that I found lacking, especially from a hotel of this caliber. (Having gotten a rock bottom price, I don't have room to complain about any of these rather minor annoyances, but many people will pay upwards of $300 per night, and they need to know what to expect.) First of all, the parking service is $40 per night, which is outrageous. Look for a nearby parking garage for $20. Secondly, there is no doorman, and the doors are heavy and difficult to open. (Struggling with a heavy 20 foot door in stiletto heels on a cold winter's night does not look chic-especially after a few martini's...). Although the doors were cumbersome, the entrance is gorgeous (palatial, to be exact). I was stunned by the exquisite architecture and lovely furnishings. The service desk was painfully slow (check-in took almost 30 minutes), but the staff was pleasant enough. My room was on the fifth floor, and was oozing with pomp and grandeur. Although the rooms are small for a hotel of this caliber, they are well decorated, and the beds are oh-so comfy (down comforter, anyone?). The 14 foot high ceilings (complete with gorgeous crown mouldings) lend an airy feel to the otherwise small room. The bathroom and closet are huge, but the showerhead/bathtub is nondescript (think: Holiday Inn) and the toiletries are sub-par (kudos to whomever mentioned the trashy toiletries earlier). All in all, this hotel is definitely worth every penny up to about $220 per night, but if you want to pay more than that, there are better places to stay. This hotel would be worth the $300 price tag if they had better service people, upgraded the showerheads/bathtubs, and offered a better toiletry selection. Oh, they should also lower the crazy $40 a night parking fee.	
Nov 29 2004	Wrong Choice	My wife and I stayed here the last week of October 04. We were with a large convention, and the Palace was in the middle of a strike by virtually all workers.The protesters were loud and woke us up every am at 6 when they started.Service was just ok for a &quot;regular&quot; hotel. But for a first class hotel at over $300 per night it was not good.They only changed towels daily if you begged them. It took till 4 pm to get it clean anyway.For very little cost to them, they could have offered their breakfast buffet for free during the strike. Instead of the $24.00 PER PERSON plus tax and tip they did charge. With it almost impossible to get a coffee refill.Or a lower room rate then agreed when we originally contracted.I will try another downtown SF hotel in the future. There are lots of choices.	
